$BODY = <<<'HTML'
<p>You switch off the light and the ringing seems to turn up the volume. Minutes pass, frustration arrives, and sleep becomes a battle lost from the start. It is one of the most difficult aspects of tinnitus — and also one of the most manageable.</p>

<h2>The cycle to break</h2>
<p>Tinnitus and insomnia feed each other: the ringing makes falling asleep hard, the tiredness of the next day makes the ringing heavier, and the anxiety of "I won't manage to sleep" keeps the nervous system alert precisely when it should stop. Breaking even one link weakens the whole chain.</p>

<h2>The plan, step by step</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Soft sound all night.</strong> Pink or brown noise, rain or wind at low volume: reduces the contrast between the ringing and silence, from evening to morning.</li>
  <li><strong>Consistent schedules.</strong> Go to bed and wake at the same time, even at weekends: the body learns when it is time to sleep.</li>
  <li><strong>The last hour of calm.</strong> Low lighting, no screens: blue light wakes the brain.</li>
  <li><strong>The 20-minute rule.</strong> If you cannot fall asleep, do not stay and fight: get up, go to another room with low light and soft sound and return only when you feel sleepy.</li>
  <li><strong>Slow breathing.</strong> Inhale <span class="num">4</span> seconds, exhale <span class="num">6–8</span>: a long exhale activates the calming part of the nervous system.</li>
</ul>

<h2>When something more is needed: CBT-I</h2>
<p>If insomnia lasts weeks, cognitive behavioural therapy for insomnia (CBT-I) is the most effective treatment, often superior to sleeping pills and without dependence. It combines well with cognitive behavioural therapy for tinnitus, which reduces tinnitus-related distress by <span class="num">10.91</span> THI points (Cochrane review, 2,733 patients). Ask your doctor about it: it is an investment that lasts.</p>

<h2>What NOT to do</h2>
<p>Avoid complete silence (it intensifies the ringing), alcohol as a "sleeping pill" (it fragments sleep), clock-watching and "checking" whether the tinnitus is still there. Every check tells the brain this sound is significant — and that is the opposite of what you want to teach it.</p>

<h2>In short</h2>
<p>Insomnia from tinnitus is a cycle, not a sentence. A soft sound all night, consistent schedules, the 20-minute rule and slow breathing break the chain; for persistent insomnia, CBT-I is the most solid solution. Sleep gradually returns — with method.</p>
